{
  "text": "Constrained Bayesian optimization as proposed by [CITATION_1] incorporates constraints with the original optimization metric. It modifies the surrogate function with a probability term associated with the fulfillment of the constraint. Let Cm(x) represent the m th constraint condition, which indicates if the constraint is satisfied at x. Then, the probabilistic constraint is P (Cm(x)) \u2265 1 \u2212 \u03b4m where 1 \u2212 \u03b4m is a user specified minimum confidence for the m th constraint. All M constraints have to be satisfied. Assuming independence amongst them, they are modelled by independent GPs. This can be done by specifying the constraints by a function gm(x) such that gm(x) \u2265 0 only if Cm(x) is satisfied.The surrogate function in (4) is modified to",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "948625"
